evelops his concept of diasporic heteroglossia, which is fiction’s unique ability to contain multiple voices that resist and write back against national centres. This work makes an important and original contribution to Jewish studies, diaspora studies, and world literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican fictionxJewish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian fictionxJewish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aJewish diaspora in literature. 0aZionism and literature. 0aZionism in literature. 4aArea Studies / Diaspora Studies. 4aArea Studies / Middle Eastern Studies. 4aArea Studies / Palestinian Studies. 4aArea Studies. 4aLiterary Studies / Literary Criticism. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh  aAnti-Zionist.  aAyelet Tsabari.  aDaniel and Jonathan Boyarin.  aDavid Bezmozgis.  aDiaspora.  aDiasporic Fiction.  aEthical Responsibility.  aIsrael.  aJewish Fiction.  aLeon Uris.  aMikhail Bakhtin.  aPalestine.  aPhilip Roth.  aTheodor Herzl.  aWorld Literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978177212695240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781772126952423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781772126952/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packageb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles